================================================================================
RESTRICTION: PURE LOGIC CONTROL TECHNOLOGY (Solver-Based Control Architecture)
================================================================================

COMMERCIAL USE OF THE FOLLOWING IS PROHIBITED without explicit written license:

"Pure Logic Control Technology" means the SPECIFIC ARCHITECTURAL COMBINATION of
the following innovations:

1. DECLARATIVE STATE GOVERNANCE
   The method of controlling system outputs by defining "Valid States" via
   bitvector constraints within a satisfiability solver, rather than by
   executing imperative instruction loops (e.g., scan cycles).

2. GEOMETRIC TEMPORAL CONTROL
   The use of native temporal indexing (e.g., x[t] vs x[t-n]) within a logic
   solver to strictly define valid physical transitions and history-dependent
   behavior without the use of memory registers, timers, or accumulators.

3. LOGICAL INVARIANT ENFORCEMENT ("The Unbreakable Guard")
   The architecture of embedding high-priority safety constraints into the
   control logic such that unsafe physical states are rendered mathematically
   unsatisfiable (UNSAT) by the solver, preventing conflicting control signals.

4. SATISFIABILITY-BASED SIGNAL FILTERING
   The method of filtering sensor input by defining logical plausibility
   constraints (e.g., "Physics forbids change > X") and using the solver to
   reject data that violates these constraints.

5. DISCRETE RESOLUTION OF CONTINUOUS DYNAMICS
   The method of mapping continuous error ranges to discrete logical regimes
   (e.g., "Panic", "Hold", "Recover") via logical implication rules, enabling
   complex non-linear control response without floating-point arithmetic.

